If you have a mouth and vocal cords, you can sing.

While everyone has the ability to sing, those who want to be great need to work hard at their craft.

Here’s how to train your voice to become a great singer.

What is Voice Training?

Voice training is a transformative process that empowers individuals to harness the full potential of their voices. At its core, it is a structured regimen designed to develop and refine singing abilities. This musical journey encompasses various elements, including pitch accuracy, breath control, tone quality, and emotional expression.

As singers begin voice training, they enter into a world where technical precision meets artistic expression. Through a combination of exercises, techniques, and personalized guidance, voice training not only enhances vocal prowess but also nurtures confidence, versatility, and the ability to connect with audiences on a profound level.

Voice training is an investment in the development of a skill set that extends beyond singing. It is a holistic approach to one’s own self-expression, allowing individuals to explore the intricacies of their voices, unraveling layers of potential that may remain undiscovered without dedicated guidance.

10 Benefits of Voice Training

Improved Vocal Range

Voice training is instrumental when it comes to expanding a singer’s vocal range. Through targeted exercises, individuals can gradually extend their reach, unlocking the ability to hit higher and lower notes–ones they thought they might never be able to sing. This expanded range enhances versatility and allows singers to tackle a broader repertoire of songs.

Enhanced Breath Control

A crucial aspect of voice training is the development of effective breath control. Singers learn to manage their breath support, ensuring sustained phrases and powerful performances. This skill not only contributes to overall vocal endurance but also enhances the quality and control of their singing.

Refined Tone Quality

Voice training places a significant emphasis on cultivating a rich and pleasing tone quality. Singers work on achieving a balanced and resonant sound, refining their vocal timbre to convey emotions and capture the attention of listeners. This focus on tone quality adds depth and expressiveness to their performances.

Increased Artistic Expression

Through voice training, singers refine their ability to convey emotions and tell stories through their voice. This heightened level of artistic expression allows for more compelling and authentic performances, fostering a deeper connection with the audience. The best singers aren’t just technically proficient, they’re also some of the most expressive.

Improved Pitch Accuracy

Voice training aims to enhance pitch accuracy, ensuring that singers can consistently hit the right notes. This precision is crucial for delivering polished and professional performances, whether in the studio or on stage.

Boosted Confidence

As singers progress in their voice training, they gain confidence in their abilities. The mastery of vocal techniques and the refinement of their voice empower individuals to tackle a diverse range of songs and musical styles with assurance.

Improved Diction and Pronunciation

Clear communication is essential when it comes to singing, and voice training often includes exercises to improve diction and pronunciation. This ensures that listeners can understand the lyrics, enhancing the overall impact of the performance. A vocalist who mumbles or sings too aggressively, garbling the words, will never be the best they can be.

Cultivated Stage Presence

Voice training extends beyond vocal techniques to encompass stage presence. Singers learn how to engage with their audience, exude confidence on stage, and use body language to enhance their overall performance.

Professional Networking Opportunities

The full scope of voice training often involves interaction with vocal coaches, fellow musicians, and potentially, industry professionals. This networking aspect can open doors to collaboration, mentorship, and valuable connections within the music industry.

Lifelong Learning and Personal Growth

Voice training is a journey of continuous improvement and discovery. It fosters a mindset of lifelong learning, encouraging singers to explore new genres, techniques, and musical concepts. This commitment to growth extends beyond just singing, positively influencing various aspects of personal development.

How to Train Your Voice In 13 Steps

Understand Your Vocal Range

Begin your voice training journey by gaining a deep understanding of your vocal range. Identify not only the highest and lowest notes you can comfortably sing but also explore the nuances within your range. This detailed awareness serves as the foundation for targeted vocal exercises that cater specifically to your unique capabilities. Pay close attention to the transitional points between different vocal registers, allowing for a more detailed exploration of your vocal capabilities.

Warm-Up Your Voice

Elevate the significance of vocal warm-ups in your daily practice routine. Before delving into more challenging exercises or song rehearsals, dedicate ample time to gentle warm-ups. These exercises not only prepare your vocal cords for the demands of singing but also contribute to a more flexible and responsive voice. Incorporate variations in warm-up intensity to gradually ease into your practice session, ensuring a smooth and controlled vocal transition.

Practice Breathing Exercises

Develop a balanced and detailed approach to breath control through dedicated breathing exercises. Beyond the basics, work on exercises that focus on different aspects of breath management, such as controlling the release of air and maintaining consistent support throughout various vocal phrases. Explore diaphragmatic breathing in various positions, incorporating seated, standing, and lying down postures to adapt to different singing scenarios.

Explore Vocal Exercises for Pitch Accuracy

Elevate your pitch accuracy by incorporating a diverse range of exercises targeting different intervals. From simple scales to more complex melodic patterns, systematically explore exercises that challenge and refine your ability to hit the right notes consistently. Experiment with exercises that specifically target intervals outside your comfort zone, gradually expanding your pitch accuracy and overall vocal control.

Refine Tone Quality

Take a deeper dive into refining your tone quality by experimenting with a broader spectrum of exercises. In addition to sustained vowel exercises, explore some that emphasize specific elements like resonance, dynamics, and smooth transitions between different registers. Incorporate vowel modification exercises to refine your ability to produce a consistent and resonant tone across various vocal styles and genres.

Emphasize Artistic Expression

Elevate your artistic expression by working to perform songs with diverse emotional themes. Delve into the emotional differences between each and every piece you try, experimenting with different vocal dynamics and phrasing to cultivate a more profound and authentic connection with your audience. Explore vocal embellishments and improvisational techniques to enhance your ability to convey a wide range of emotions through your singing. These are the differences that will make you stand out from all other vocalists.

Interpret and Analyze Lyrics

Extend your focus to interpreting lyrics by selecting a variety of songs with meaningful and diverse lyrical content. Learn the stories behind the lyrics, which will allow for a deeper understanding and which will inform your vocal interpretation, resulting in more authentic and emotionally resonant performances. Experiment with lyric analysis techniques to uncover layers of meaning and convey the intended emotions with greater depth and authenticity.

Improve Diction and Pronunciation

Dedicate focused practice sessions to enhancing your diction and pronunciation. Engage in exercises that specifically target articulation, ensuring that every word is clear and easily understood by your audience, which will further enhance the impact of your vocal delivery. Explore techniques such as tongue twisters and consonant-focused exercises to refine your ability to enunciate words distinctly in various musical performances.

Experiment with Different Genres

Broaden your vocal versatility by exploring songs from an even wider array of genres than you’re used to. Challenge yourself with genres that may be less familiar, as each style presents unique vocal challenges, and this practice will foster a more well-rounded and adaptable singing style. Study the historical and cultural contexts of different musical genres, which will grant you a deeper understanding to influence your vocal approach and interpretation.

Record Yourself

Transform the act of recording into a comprehensive self-assessment tool. In addition to recording your practice sessions and performances, learn how to be more analytical with these recordings. Identify specific areas for improvement, scrutinize your technique, and celebrate milestones in your vocal journey. Utilize recording technology to experiment with different microphone techniques, allowing for a better understanding of how your voice translates in various recording environments.

Engage in Regular Vocal Lessons

Elevate the impact of vocal lessons by actively engaging in continuous learning. Work closely with your vocal coach–if you find one–to set personalized goals, study advanced techniques, and explore diverse musical genres, ensuring a dynamic and evolving approach to your vocal development. Actively participate in goal-setting sessions with your coach, fostering a collaborative and tailored approach to your vocal journey.

Stay Consistent with Practice

Make sure you stay consistent with your practice routine. Don’t let life get in the way of practicing, which is no easy feat! Beyond establishing a regular practice schedule, consider incorporating diverse elements into your routine, including targeted exercises, explorations of new material, and opportunities for creative improvisation, ensuring a well-rounded and evolving approach. Experiment with incorporating mindfulness and meditation practices into your routine to foster mental focus and heightened awareness during practice sessions.

Seek Constructive Feedback

Cultivate a mindset of being receptive to constructive feedback by actively seeking input from vocal coaches, fellow musicians, and trusted friends. Regularly engage in reflective sessions where you actively identify areas for improvement, celebrate achievements, and maintain a growth-oriented mindset in your vocal journey. Actively participate in constructive feedback, fostering a collaborative and supportive community that contributes to the ongoing refinement of your vocal skills.

10 Tips To Keep Your Voice Safe

Stay Hydrated

Emphasize the importance of staying adequately hydrated for vocal health. Beyond merely drinking water, consider incorporating hydrating foods into your diet, ensuring your vocal cords remain lubricated and capable of optimal performance. Drink plenty of herbal teas and throat-soothing beverages to enhance hydration and promote overall vocal well-being.

Avoid Excessive Caffeine and Alcohol

Learn more about the impact of caffeine and alcohol on vocal health. Beyond limiting consumption, explore alternative beverages and hydration practices that positively contribute to maintaining vocal moisture. Experiment with caffeine-free herbal teas and explore the impact of different hydration strategies on your vocal endurance.

Practice Good Vocal Hygiene

Confirm your commitment to vocal hygiene by actively avoiding excessive throat clearing or yelling. In addition to these precautions, explore vocal warm-up exercises specifically designed to enhance your vocal hygiene practices. Experiment with gentle vocal massage techniques to promote blood circulation and alleviate tension in the vocal muscles.

Use Vocal Rest When Necessary

Vocal fatigue is a real thing, and you can keep it at bay by proactively incorporating periods of vocal rest when needed. Develop a personalized strategy for vocal rest, considering factors such as speaking limitations and gentle vocal exercises to gradually reintroduce your voice. Experiment with vocal relaxation techniques, such as humming and lip trills, during periods of vocal rest to maintain vocal flexibility.

Warm-Up Before Performances

Add to your pre-performance warm-up routine by incorporating a more comprehensive set of vocal warm-up exercises. Tailor your warm-up to the specific demands of your performance, ensuring that your voice is optimally prepared for the nuances of the material. Toy around with longer warm-up sessions that include dynamic stretches and vocal exercises targeting specific vocal challenges you may encounter during the performance.

Protect Your Voice in Noisy Environments

Be wary of your own vocal protection in noisy environments by actively seeking out effective ear protection. Play around with different types of products to identify the most comfortable and efficient options for maintaining vocal clarity. Explore noise-canceling technology and custom-fit ear protection to tailor your approach to various performance settings. Sometimes, a simple earplug will do, and make sure not to strain your voice by shouting too much.

Avoid Smoking

Smoking is one of the worst things you can do as a singer when it comes to your vocal health. Maintain a smoke-free lifestyle for the long-term health of your voice–and the rest of your body as well. If you haven’t started, don’t! If you’re already a smoker, there’s no better time to quit than right now.

Get Adequate Sleep

The relationship between sleep and vocal health is incredibly important, and one that can’t be avoided. Ensuring sufficient and restful sleep is key to unlocking your best performance. Consider incorporating relaxation techniques into your pre-sleep routine to enhance overall vocal well-being.

Practice Vocal Exercises Mindfully

Stay mindful when it comes to your vocal exercises. Avoid pushing your voice beyond comfortable limits, and cultivate a heightened awareness of physical sensations during vocal exercises. Learn more about mindfulness meditation techniques, which come with a bevy of benefits, including the ability to enhance focus and concentration during vocal practice sessions.

Consult a Professional for Persistent Issues

If you are having any persistent vocal issues, it’s time to look for help outside of yourself–and this article. Seek professional guidance. Beyond consultation, consider exploring additional wellness practices such as vocal massage or therapeutic interventions to address underlying concerns and promote long-term vocal well-being. You don’t want to put this off, as it’s better to deal with any issues when they arise, rather than letting them snowball.

4 Places To Learn Voice Training

Music Schools/Conservatories

Enroll in a reputable music school or conservatory such as Juilliard or Berklee College of Music, known for their world-class voice training programs, experienced faculty, and state-of-the-art facilities. These institutions often provide networking opportunities with industry professionals, enhancing your chances of establishing a successful career in vocal performance.

Pursue a Bachelor’s or Master’s degree in vocal performance at esteemed universities that offer comprehensive academic and practical training. The academic environment fosters a deep understanding of music theory, history, and performance, providing a well-rounded education for aspiring vocalists.

Private Vocal Coaches/Teachers

Seek guidance from private vocal coaches or teachers for personalized attention, tailored instruction, and accelerated progress in your vocal journey. Private lessons often allow for flexible scheduling, accommodating the unique needs and commitments of individual learners. They don’t come cheap, but if you’re dedicated to honing your craft and becoming the best vocalist possible, it’s worth the expense.

Online Platforms

Explore a multitude of voice training resources on YouTube, where established coaches like Eric Arceneaux and Felicia Ricci share valuable insights, exercises, and performance tips for singers of all levels. There are perhaps hundreds of channels on the platform that you could follow, so do some research to learn which ones are the most popular and the best. Be smart about where you receive your free advice.

Voice Training Apps

Enhance your vocal skills on the go with apps, which provide you with vocal exercises, making it a convenient and interactive tool for consistent practice and improvement. These apps often incorporate technology to track your progress, offering insights into your vocal development over time.

Example Voice Training Course

If you do decide to enroll in a college program to become a vocalist, what will you actually learn? The answer to that question varies widely, depending on where you go, what program you follow, and a number of other factors. There are some basics that will surely be taught, but each degree and teacher is different.

Below is an outline of an introductory voice class taught at Berklee–known as perhaps the most famous and important music college in the world–in the class Voice Technique 101. This should give you some insight into what you’ll actually learn in the earliest stages of your voice training courses.

Lesson 1: Developing Good Breath Support

In the initial lesson, students focus on the foundation of vocal technique—breath support. Through exercises and guided practice, participants learn to engage their diaphragm effectively, control airflow, and develop the stamina required for sustained and powerful vocal delivery. Understanding the connection between breath support and vocal resonance lays the groundwork for a strong and resonant singing voice.

Lesson 2: Developing Your Vocal Sound

Building on breath support, this lesson explores the nuances of creating a unique vocal sound. Students learn about tone production, timbre, and stylistic choices, and work to develop a distinctive and authentic vocal identity. Through vocal exercises and artistic exploration, participants refine their sound, allowing for versatility and expression across various musical genres.

Lesson 3: Anatomy/Health

A crucial aspect of voice training is understanding the anatomy of the voice and maintaining vocal health. In this lesson, students study the anatomical structures involved in singing, gaining insights into vocal health practices. Topics include vocal cord care, preventing vocal strain, and recognizing signs of fatigue, fostering a holistic approach to vocal well-being, and more.

Lesson 4: Developing an Effective Practice Routine

Students learn the art of effective and efficient practice in this lesson. Emphasizing quality over quantity, participants explore strategies for structuring practice sessions, incorporating vocal exercises, and setting realistic goals. This lesson equips students with the tools to optimize their practice time and accelerate their vocal development.

Lesson 5: Simple Melodic Embellishment

Expanding vocal artistry, this lesson focuses on simple melodic embellishments, as its name suggests. Students learn techniques for adding tasteful ornamentation to melodies, enhancing expressiveness and creativity in their singing. Through practical exercises and application in various musical contexts, participants develop the skills to embellish melodies with confidence.

Lesson 6: Effective Diction for Singing

Clear and expressive communication is paramount in vocal performance. This lesson hones in on effective diction for singing, addressing articulation, vowel modification, and consonant clarity. Students refine their ability to convey lyrics with precision, ensuring that their vocal delivery is both understood and emotionally resonant.

Lesson 7: Singing Harmony

Diving into the world of vocal collaboration, this lesson explores singing harmony. Students gain proficiency in harmonizing with other voices, understanding chord structures, and contributing to ensemble performances. The ability to sing harmony enhances versatility and opens up opportunities for collaborating with countless other performers.

Lesson 8: Advanced Breath Management

Building upon the foundational breath support lesson, students then progress into advanced breath management techniques. This lesson focuses on mastering breath control in challenging musical passages, sustaining long phrases, and navigating dynamic changes. Participants refine their breath management skills for heightened vocal control and expression.

Lesson 9: Performance Polish

Preparing for the stage, this lesson concentrates on the finer aspects of performance, letting those studying polish their presentation. Students learn stage presence, audience engagement, and techniques for overcoming performance anxiety. Through simulated performance scenarios and constructive feedback, participants shine their stagecraft for compelling and confident live performances.

Lesson 10: Flexibility, Control, Stamina

In this lesson, students work on enhancing vocal flexibility, control, and stamina. Through targeted exercises, participants develop the agility to navigate vocal runs, dynamic control for expressive singing, and the stamina required for extended performances. This lesson equips students with the vocal prowess needed for demanding musical challenges.

Lesson 11: The Essential Building Blocks of Voice Training

A comprehensive review and integration of key voice training concepts, this lesson consolidates the essential building blocks. Students revisit breath support, vocal sound development, diction, and other foundational elements, fostering a holistic understanding of the interconnected facets of vocal technique.

Lesson 12: The Grand Finale

The culmination of the course, the “Grand Finale” lesson celebrates the journey of vocal development. Students showcase their progress through individual performances, integrating the skills acquired throughout the course. This final section serves as a testament to the students’ growth, providing a platform to express their unique vocal artistry with their fellow learners.
